  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "bpTQFMkp5mrPSOcrnJ3W7fsYXk8=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:44.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "# Single Writer Per Feed\n\nSwarm feeds are backed by Single Owner Chunks (SOCs). A SOC update requires a signature from the owner's private key, so each feed has exactly one writer. This is a protocol-level constraint, not a Powerhouse choice.\n\n## Implications\n\n1. There is no \"shared writable feed\" \u2014 you cannot have Alice and Bob both pushing to one topic\n2. Collaboration must be modeled as N writer feeds, one per participant\n3. The collaboration index feed (itself single-writer by the creator) tells everyone where to subscribe\n4. Each reader fans out across N-1 peer feeds to observe all edits\n\n## Design consequence\n\nThe single-writer rule is why the op-feed layout uses `ph:v2:ops:<address>:<docId>` \u2014 address is part of the topic so each participant owns a distinct feed space for the same document. Without this, two participants would collide on the same topic and only one could actually write.\n",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:44.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:44.000Z"
    }
  },
